{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696404/1930112401/0053.xml":{"full_text":"SHE KILLED A WOMAN FOR HIS LOVE-BUT EVEN THAT IS DEAD NOW\nMH m1\niMI Mfet\u2019 Vl\u00bb 11\n\"y IF B B wrMBwWIB\ni\"\" teSyil I bMhI\naOLm HIM I HB\nI y.J l x Wa 1 1 t JI p\n'ST !te >raWlK.' --W< wi faM I'lfl\u00df iii\nRHhhmL\nSr\u2022 J \u25a0b\u00bb\u2019>-\ns\u00a3*\u201e\u201481/\n:^_y mo\nF -te' R\n1I\nz Mi w MM< IMM.\n\nv Mb MMBwEiW\nWJMaHS. hPmRb\nII B I\nMRS. GAMBLE AND BILLY\nLAST SEPTEMBER Mrs. Gamble, of La Plata, Md\u201e loved her\nhusband enough to kill Mrs. Elsie Davis when she found her in a\ncar with him. Today that love is dead, killed, she said, when he\nASSASSIN FIRES\nON IRISH CHIEF\nDUBLIN, Nov. 24 (1.N.5.).\nStrict secrecy continued today to\nveil what is believed to have been\nan attempt to kill Gen. Richard\nMulcahy, minister of public\nhealth, last night.\nThe official escaped injury, but\none of his guards suffered a\nknee wound and was taken to the\nhospital.\nGeneral Mulcahy, it was under\nstood, accompanied by a number\nof friends, was about to enter the\nresidence of Prof. Hayes, speaker\nof the Dail, when a shot was\nfired. Plain clothes men im\nmediately returned fire. A mo\nment later several men were seen\ndashing away.\nOfficial sources were reticent\nabout the incident.\nRumors were current that Prof.\nHayes had been wounded, but\nthese could not be confirmed.\nStepped on, He Hits Man, 93\nHW 1 .-1 s\n.s i\nzgjMifc.;. W\nEH JE|b \u00aba\u00dfKfe\nJ^^JtM&jK-\n.\u25a0js- K|\nW W J\ngaaBMMMSMMEMMw\u00abXS3&%iws&\nw |Mp~- K fc >J|\ny O w ;i\nT r\ni| ?felfii p|^ill\nIBWgWWH^WwMOIMMi I \\Jlr OHi Io w\nk |fc Jilll 1 I\nSg mB I I\n-\u25a0HBiIB lli IBi 1 B 8\n9E BMeMMaSire 81-: z MF m? ffiilSaMM\u00dfl\nfc w\nIwP I\n1 is^^Kii*< t Wlp\nO\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nHENRY MYER SPRINGMAN AND .WALKER\nHENRY MYER, 93, living in a rooming house in the 300 block Pennsylvania Avenue,\nstepped on Samuel Walker\u2019s toes. Samuel. 75, resented it. A fuss resulted and Samuel,\ntwo weeks after the toe-stepping, felled Myer last night with the iron bar Detective\nJim Springman is holding. In court this morning the two men refused to make up and\nthe judge ordered Walker to move.\nBankers Ready to Assist\nTax-Harassed Jobless\nProperty owners who are un\nto meet taxes, payments or re\nable, because of unemployment,\npair bills on their homes are\nurged to confer with their bank\ners, in a report to the special\ncommittee on unemployment of\nthe Federation of Citizens\u2019 Asso\nciations, made by Edwin S.\nHegge, subcommittee chairman.\nMr. Hegge\u2019s report declares\n.that the committee found lead\ning bankers of the District ready\nto help home owners with such\nproblems.\nFrank Statement Urged\nMr. Hegge adds:\n\u201cA depositor or real estate note\nmaker, finding himself short of\nfunds for urgent needs, would\ndo well to call promptly on his\nbanker for a full and frank dis\ncussion of the problem and a\nremedy. While each case may\nhave its own peculiarities and\nthu\u00a7 preclude a general rule even\nfor all cases of the same type,\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nit is believed that worthy per\nsons need not be hesitant nor\ndiscouraged at the prospect of\nobtaining aid at their banks.\n\u201cFor example, if the maker of\na first trust real estate note can\nnot meet the monthly payments\non his home, the bank may be\nable to accept interest propor\ntionate to monthly payments\nfor several months and extend\nthe note by a corresponding\nperiod.\u201d\nRepairs Now Will Help\nThe report also urged all per\nsons who have repair work to be\ndone to hasten the work and thus\nprovide employment. The sugges\ntion is advanced that Christmas\nsavings funds be used for jobs\nabout the home.\n\u2022The committee on unemploy\nment is also studying a plan of\ncircularizing numbers of the va\nrious citizens\u2019 associations with a\nview to increase employment.\nJOSEPH GAMBLE TENDS HIS BEES\ntook the stand against her in her trial last week, at which she was\nacquitted. Gamble continues to tend his bees at his La Plata home,\nwhile Mrs. Gamble, with her son, Billy, stays at a hotel.\nNEGRO SCHOOLS\nHELD TOO FEW\nThe degree of education which\nthe negro possesses in this coun\ntry has enabled him to become\ndissatisfied with his present edu\ncational status, declared Dr. John\nW. Davis,, prominent negro edu\ncator and president of West Vir\nginia State College, here yester\nday.\nDr. Davis, who is a member of\nPresident Hoover\u2019s educational\ncommittee along with Dr. Robert\nR. Moton, principal of Tuskegee\nInstitute and Dr. Mordecai John\nson, president of Howard Uni\nversity, said there are in Amer\nica about 50 colored graduates\nupon whom American and for\neign universities have conferred\nthe degree of doctor of philoso\nphy, 20,000 with baccalaureate\ndegrees, about 23,000 now en\nrolled in colleges and 50.000\nteachers for nearly three and\na half million pupils.\nCharges Neglect\nIn the South, he declared,\nnegro education is neglected to\na great degree.\nFourteen of the southern\nStates show a total of 256 ac\ncredited high schools for negroes.\nWhite teachers received an\nnually a salary of about SI,OOO\nand negro teachers $478 in these\nStates. The term of school days\nis 162 for the white and 135\nfor the colored.\nNeed Million\nSpeaking of the 17 negro land\ngrant colleges, of which West Vir\nginia State College is one, Dr\nDavis said, $338,000 is received\nannually for the colored institu\ntions out of $13,000,000 from\nFederal land grants.\nIt would require nearly three\nmillion dollars a year to bring\nthe negro colleges up to similar\nstandards of the white, he said.\nMoney Can\u2019t Buy Better Teeth\nPlatea Repaired While You Wait\nAll Work Done in My Own\nLaboratories\nNo Lons Waiting\u2014No High Prices\nCrown and Bridge Work\n$5 <uxn*ss\nEXTRACTIONS, >I.OO\u2014BT GAS. F\u2019.OC\nDR. SMATHERS\nDental Specialist\n027 SEVENTH ST. N. W.\nAcross from Goldenberg\u2019s and Orel\nPeoples Drog Store\nHours, oa.m.to\u00df p. m. Ph. Met. 9858\n$2.95 and $2.45\nKid Glove*\nNovelty Cuffs and Slip-On*\nSpecial, $1.95\nAll Size*\nJ. B. JONES CO.\n1219-21 G St. N. W.\nt-\nWatc/i This Paper for,\nSpecial Announcement by\n314-316 7th St. N.W.\nThe National Daily\nRACE CONGRESS\nHERE TONIGHT\nA conference tomorrow at noon\nwith President Hoover at the\nWhite House will be among the\nfeatures of the annual conven\ntion of the National Equal Rights\nLeague and Race Congress, which\nopens here tonight at the John\nWesley A. M. E. Zion Church.\nFourteenth and Corcoran Streets\nNorthwest.\nDelegates of the conference will\nmeet the President.and urge him\nto sponsor an \u201canti-lynching\nweek.\u201d This appeal is a part of\nthe program of the Equal Rights\nLeague, which is holding a na\ntional anti-lynching congress to\nface the alarming increase of\nlynching during 1930.\nUp until the present date, twice\nas many lynchings have occurred\nthroughout the country as were\ncommitted during the entire year\nof 1929. The appeal is sponsored\nby Bishop J. W. Walls, of the Afri\ncan Methodist Episcopal Zion\nChuich; the Rev. B. W. Swain,\nof Louisville, Ky.; William Mon\nroe Trotter, of Boston, and Mau\nrice Spencer of this city. The con\nvention will close Wednesday.\nNegro Gets 30 Years\nFor Knife Slaying\nA 30-year prison sentence was\nimposed on Harry Brown, negro\nslayer of James P. Taylor, in\nCriminal Court yesterday by Jus\ntice Oscar R. Luhring. Brown\nwas convicted of second degree\nmurder.\nBrown stabbed Taylor to death\nlast August 1, during a quarrel\nover Taylor\u2019s wife.\neSee|\nMONDAY\u2014NOVEMBER 24\u20141930\nn \u2022\u00bb:-amiMMHBatM\ntte l\n\u25a0WT I OJ II\n7| 1 5\nr\nIt yA xfc. >MM|Mmm\nI\nI r Lx Jiw\nk\nS\nBfe-*-- 1 \u2018WMk wmHB-\nU HBKW\n\nMMMMMMMB mBBMMHMMOTMH\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nJANEY BESS IE CHESTER\nTRAGEDY HAS STALKED TWICE through the home of Gamble\u2014once when\nMrs. Gamble shot Mrs. Elsie Davis, and again when -Gamble, taking the stand\nagainst his wife, said he was through with her. Meanwhile, Janey, Bessie and\nChester help to keep the dishes clean, while mother is stopping at a hotel.\nMISSING AFTER\nGRID GAME\nPolice were today investigating\nthe mysterious disappearance of\nWilliam; L. Studley. 47, of 1302\nEighteenth St. N. W., who failed\nto return to his home last night\nafter attending the Yale-Harvard\nfootball game at New Haven,\nConn., Saturday.\nMrs. Studley received a tele\ngram from her husband yester\nday saying that he would arrive\nat Union Station at 5:30 last\nnight. When he failed to reach\nthis city, relatives communicated\nwith a telegraph company in\nNew York and learned that the\ntelegram had been sent from the\nPennsylvania Station a few min\nutes before the noon train was to\nleave for Washington.\nInspector William S. Shelby,\nchief of detectives, today detailed\na man to investigate whether a\nseat on a Pullman, reserved by\nMr. Studley, had been used.\nMrs. Studley said she can\nascribe no reason for her hus\nband\u2019s disappearance.\nMrs. Studley, communicating\nwith the Yale Club in New York,\nwhere her husband had been\nstopping, learned that Mr. Stud\nley had checked out early yester\nday for Washington.\nAT YOUR THEATER TONIGHT I\nOFFICIAL PROGRAMS of Theater members of the\nMotion Picture Theater Owners of District of Columbia\nFOX Fat Fourteenth WARNER BROS. THEATERS\nEl Brendel and Maureen O\u2019Sullivan WWfill 11 Ball V\nin \u201cJEST IMAGINE\u201d\nStage\u2014Fanchon Marco \u201cSmiles\u201d Idea HUDAQQAnfiD 18th St. and Col. EADIE Thirteenth Street\nLeon Brusiloff and Fox Music Masters AWIDAwdAUUII Rd. N. W. tAlluE Below 1 Street\nRON AND DON ORGANLOGUE _ ...dttvv mtttttr\nFOX MOVIETONE NEWS MARILYN MILLER On the Screen\u2014MARILYN MILLER\nin in SUNN*\nnil lAF r 04- 10*k \"SUNNY\u201d On the Stage\u2014BELLE BAKER and\nr PALACE F St at 13th jo\u00ae donahue.\nW\u2019M. HAINES A FOLLY MORAN inftl Isl 624 H Street\nOin \u201cREMOTE CONTROL\u201d ArULLU Northeast Ufllir 12,n C Str<et\nStare\u2014Wesley Eddy in \u201cRustic HU Wife Northeast\nE Fancies.\u201d Palace Syncopators LEWIS AYRES In\nHearst Metrotone News \u201cALL QUIET ON THE WESTERN BERT WHEELER and\nFRONT\u201d ROBERT WOOLSEY In\nCOLUMBIA- FSt.atUth A\nMarie Dressier and Wallace Beery MIALUIt McKinley St.. D. C.\nS Short LEWIS AYRES in METROPOLITAN\nSubjects. Columbia Orchestra. \u201cALL QUIET ON THE WESTERN RSI IlVr VMIRR\nmwm..as. .2 FRONT\u201d (\"[.OSED\u2014REOPENING WEDNESDAY\nRFPIIRI IP Phone North 7\u00bb56\u25a0 \\T R :40 P. M.\nnCFUDLIU u St. Near 14th. ADMIID \u00ab5 P\u00ab. Ave. With \u201cOUTWARD BOUND\u201d\n\u201cTHE SILVER HORDE\u201d AVFNUE GRAND Southeast\nwith Evelyn Brent and Louis Wolheim U UMBU llth Colnmhi\u00df Rd\nm-IT Bethesda. KAT J HI SON SAVOY Northwest\n0 I A I t Md. \u201cMADAM SATAN\u201d JOHN GILBERT in\nWestern Electric Sound System vriUnunv/ VARIETY\nGRETA GARBO PEBITDAI Ninth St. Between VITAPHONE A ARIETY\nin \u201cBOMANCJC\u201d Util I HAL D and E Sts.\nL LINCOLN K -a.M. TIVOLI\nI \"The Cat Creeps\u201d\u2014Helen Twelve- VITAPHONE VARIETY CONRAD NAGEL\nC trees. Neil Hamilton ALHyan Tash- r 4 nv \u00ab;rnRFNDFRS\u201d\nman. Thrills! Shivers! Laughter! fl Al AMV Georgia Avenue and A LADY SLRRENDE\nfl VULUHI larragut St. VADIf Georgia Avenue and\nm BOOKER T BERT WHEELER and YORK Quebec Street\nT ww asanas a (talkie) ROBERT WOOLSEY In ANN HARDING in\nNancy Carroll in \"LAUGHTER\" \u201cHALF SHOT AT SUNRISE\u201d \u201cGIRL OF THE GOLDEN WEST\u201d\nM VITAPHONE VARIETY COMEDY\nA ROSALIA 2,8 rst s\nf|,l> Garbo\u2014\u201cROMANCE\u201d TAKOMA F ir,h and B tternn J\u2019 R-R-Q KEITHS S Mh\nRRw AOWAY Talking Pictures at Their Best \u201cTOL\u2019ABLE DAVID.\u201d with Richard\nSMHMOMuni (Near Fl RONALD COLMAN in Cromwell. Noah Beery and Joan Feers.\nNancy Carroll\u2014 Follow Thru.\" \"RAFFLES\" Usual Subsidiary Offerings.\nThree District Clubs\nVote Heavily For\nDry Repeal\nThree of Washington\u2019s lead\ning clubs favor the repeal of\nprohibition.\nThis was the answer hurled\ntoday by the Washington\nCrusaders. an organization\nworking for a change in the\ndry law. to the statement made\nrecently by a member of the\nW. C. T. U. that \u201cevery good\nman and woman wants prohibi\ntion.\u201d\nThe Crusaders recently\na poll of the Metropolitan,\nCosmos and Army and Navy\nclubs, and 80.3 per cent of the\n446 replies showed sentiment\nfor change in the dry law.\nLaGuardia Asks Quiz\nOs Bankruptcy Ring\nThe Department of Justice\nsign a federal district judge andF\nwas today requested by Repre\nsentative LaGuardia (R.), of\nNew York, to assign a Federal\ndistrict judge and a special assis\ntant attorney general to conduct\na grand jury investigation into an\nalleged bankruptcy ring in Mem\nphis, Tenn.\nAssignment of a judge for this\npurpose would relieve Federal\nJudge Harry B. Anderson, of\nMemphis, now under investiga\ntion by the House Judiciary Com\nmittee. of any connection with the\ninquiry.\n573.6D0 IS PAID\nFOR DNE AD\nThe return of prosperity and\nof public buying power to the na\ntion is heralded in the striking\naction of the Grigsby-Grunow\nCompany and the Majestic\nHousehold Utilities Corporation\nin placing the largest single ad\nvertisement ever given to any\nwoman\u2019s magazine in the De\ncember issue of Good Housekeep\ning.\nThe advertisement is an eight\npage, four-color insert, costing\n$73,600, and presenting the larg\nest expenditure of money by any\nsingle manufacturer in any single\nmagazine issue, so far as is\nknown.\nThe advertisement places be\nfore the public the new Majes\ntic electrical refrigerator.\nSoldier Hit by Auto\nSuffers Broken Leg\nKnocked down by an automo\nbile in the 6600 block of Georgia\nAve. N. W., yesterday, Edward\nHalem, 34, a soldier stationed at\nWalter Reed Hospital suffered a\nfractured leg. He is being treated\nat Walter Reed Hospital.\nThe automobile was driven by\nRichard Nelson, 17, of 222 Upshur\nSt. N. W., police say.\n19","height":"30286","width":"24147"}}
